# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: babcock-wilcox
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] In scientific notation, it is written as 1×106 or 106.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] Physical quantities can also be expressed using the SI prefix mega (M), when dealing with SI units; for example, 1 megawatt (1 MW) equals 1,000,000 watts.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] The meaning of the word "million" is common to the short scale and long scale numbering systems, unlike the larger numbers, which have different names in the two systems.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] The million is sometimes used in the English language as a metaphor for a very large number, as in "Not in a million years" and "You're one in a million", or a hyperbole, as in "I've walked a million miles" and "You've asked a million-dollar question".
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] Even though it is often stressed that counting to precisely a million would be an exceedingly tedious task due to the time and concentration required, there are many ways to bring the number "down to size" in approximate quantities, ignoring irregularities or packing effects.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] In Indian English and Pakistani English, it is also expressed as 10 lakh.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] Lakh is derived from *lakṣa* for 100,000 in Sanskrit.
[src:babcock-wilcox/1-000-000] There are 78,498 primes less than 106, where 999,983 is the largest prime number smaller than 1,000,000.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:babcock-wilcox/aeolipile] This claim was denied by Spanish authorities.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron was founded in 1825 by Simon Perkins and Paul Williams at the summit of the Ohio and Erie Canal.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Its name is derived from the Greek word ἄκρον (*ákron*), meaning summit.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The canal facilitated early growth by connecting the city to regional and national markets.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the late 19th and early 20th centuries, Akron became a center of rubber and tire manufacturing; it was the headquarters of B.F.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Goodrich, Firestone, General Tire, and Goodyear (which is still based in the city) and was nicknamed the "Rubber Capital of the World".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It was also known as a center of airship development.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Today, Akron's economy includes manufacturing, education, healthcare, and biomedical research.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city is home to the University of Akron, which has a focus on polymer science based in the region's industrial legacy.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron also serves as a regional center for medical services, anchored by Akron Children's Hospital and Summa Health.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Cultural and civic institutions include the Akron Art Museum, Stan Hywet Hall and Gardens, and a network of parks integrated into the Ohio & Erie Canalway National Heritage Area.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Notable historic events in Akron include the passage of the Akron School Law of 1847, which created the K–12 system; the popularization of the church architectural Akron Plan, the foundation of Alcoholics Anonymous, the 1983 Supreme Court case *City of Akron v.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron Center for Reproductive Health*, and portions of the 2014 Gay Games.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city was the site of notable speeches on race and civil rights, including the Ain't I A Woman? speech by Sojourner Truth in 1851, W.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Du Bois in 1920, and President Bill Clinton in 1997.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Periods of civil unrest have included the riot of 1900, the rubber strike of 1936, the Wooster Avenue riots of 1968, and the 2022 protests surrounding the killing of Jayland Walker.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The first settler in the Akron area was Major Miner Spicer, who came from Groton, Connecticut.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] He built a log cabin in the forest in 1810, and became the region's first citizen.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In June 1811, Spicer sent for his family, who came that same year by ox teams accompanied by Capt.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1811, Paul Williams settled near the corner of what is now Buchtel Avenue and Broadway.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] He suggested to General Simon Perkins, who was surveyor of the Connecticut Land Company's Connecticut Western Reserve, that they found a town at the summit of the developing Ohio and Erie Canal.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The name is adapted from the Greek word ἄκρον (*ákron*), meaning summit or high point.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It was laid out in December 1825, where the south part of the downtown Akron neighborhood sits today.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Irish laborers working on the Ohio Canal built about 100 cabins nearby.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] After Eliakim Crosby founded "North Akron" (also known as Cascade) in the northern portion of what is now downtown Akron in 1833, "South" was added to Akron's name until about three years later, when the two were merged and became an incorporated village in 1836.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1840, Summit County formed from portions of Portage, Medina, and Stark Counties.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron replaced Cuyahoga Falls as its county seat a year later and opened a canal connecting to Beaver, Pennsylvania, helping give birth to the stoneware, sewer pipe, fishing tackle, and farming equipment industries.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1844, abolitionist John Brown moved into the John Brown House across the street from business partner Colonel Simon Perkins, who lived in the Perkins Stone Mansion.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron School Law of 1847 founded the city's public schools and created the K–12 grade school system, which currently is used in every U.S. state.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city's first school is now a museum on Broadway Street near the corner of Exchange.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] When the Ohio Women's Rights Convention came to Akron in 1851, Sojourner Truth extemporaneously delivered her speech named "Ain't I A Woman?", at the Universalist Old Stone Church.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1870, a local businessman associated with the church, John R.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Buchtel, founded Buchtel College, which became the University of Akron in 1913.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Ferdinand Schumacher bought a mill in 1856, and the following decade mass-produced oat bars for the Union Army during the American Civil War; these continued to sell well after the war.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Philanthropist Lewis Miller, Walter Blythe, and architect Jacob Snyder designed the widely used Akron Plan, debuting it on Akron's First Methodist Episcopal Church in 1872.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Numerous Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches built between the 1870s and World War I use it.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1883, a local journalist began the modern toy industry by founding the Akron Toy Company.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] A year later, the first popular toy was mass-produced clay marbles made by Samuel C.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Dyke at his shop where Lock 3 Park is now.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Other popular inventions include rubber balloons, ducks, dolls, balls, baby buggy bumpers, and little brown jugs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1895, the first long-distance electric railway, the Akron, Bedford and Cleveland Railroad, began service.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] On August 25, 1889, the Boston Daily Globe referred to Akron with the nickname "Summit City".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] To help local police, the city deployed the first police car in the U.S. that ran on electricity.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Riot of 1900 saw assaults on city officials, two deaths, and the destruction by fire of Columbia Hall and the Downtown Fire Station (now the City Building since 1925).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The American trucking industry was birthed through Akron's Rubber Capital of the World era when the four major tire companies B.F.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Goodrich (1869), Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company (1898), Firestone Tire and Rubber Company (1900), and General Tire & Rubber Company (1915) were headquartered in the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The numerous jobs the rubber factories provided for deaf people led to Akron being nicknamed the "Crossroads of the Deaf".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] On Easter Sunday 1913, 9.55 inches (243 mm) of rain fell, causing floods that killed five people and destroyed the Ohio and Erie Canal system.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] From 1916 to 1920, 10,000 schoolgirls took part in the successful Akron Experiment, testing iodized salt to prevent goiter in what was known as the "Goiter Belt".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1914, Marcus Garvey founded the Universal Negro Improvement Association in Kingston, Jamaica; its Akron branch opened in 1921.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Rubber companies responded to housing crunches by building affordable housing for workers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Seiberling, built the Goodyear Heights neighborhood for employees.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Firestone built the Firestone Park neighborhood for his employees.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the 1910–1920 decade, Akron became a boomtown, being America's fastest growing city with a 201.8% increase in population.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Of the 208,000 citizens, almost one-third were immigrants (also Clark Gable) and their children from places including Europe and West Virginia.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1929 and 1931, Goodyear's subsidiary Goodyear-Zeppelin Company manufactured two airships for the United States Navy, USS *Akron* (ZRS-4) and USS *Macon* (ZRS-5).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Goodyear built a number of blimps for the Navy during WWII and later for advertising purposes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron again grew when Kenmore was annexed by voter approval on November 6, 1928.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Found hiding under a bed at one of his hideouts in the city, notorious bank robber Charles Arthur "Pretty Boy" Floyd was arrested under the name "Frank Mitchell" in March 1930.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Goodyear became America's top tire manufacturer after merging with the Kelly-Springfield Tire Company in 1935.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Lasting five weeks and consisting of roughly 5,000 strikers including union sympathizers from other factories and neighboring states, the Akron Rubber Strike of 1936 successfully used the "sit-down" tactic to force recognition of the United Rubber Workers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the 1950s–60s Akron surged as use of the automobile did.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The historic Rubber Bowl was used by the National Guard of the United States as a base during the racial Wooster Avenue Riots of 1968.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Like many other industries of the Rust Belt, both the tire and rubber industries experienced major decline.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] By the early 1990s, Goodyear was the last major tire manufacturer based in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Despite the number of rubber workers decreasing by roughly half from 2000 to 2007, Akron's research in polymers gained an international reputation.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It now centers on the Polymer Valley which consists of 400 polymer-related companies, of which 94 were located in the city itself.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Research is focused at the University of Akron, which is home to the Goodyear Polymer Center and the National Polymer Innovation Center, and the College of Polymer Science and Polymer Engineering.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Because of its contributions to the Information Age, *Newsweek* listed Akron fifth of ten high-tech havens in 2001.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2008 "City of Invention" was added to the seal when the All-America City Award was received for the third time.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Bridgestone built a new technical center with state-of-the-art R&D labs and moved its product development operations to the new facility in early 2012.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2013, the Goodyear Tire & Rubber Company opened its new global headquarters on Innovation Way, further cementing the company's relationship with the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Some events of the 2014 Gay Games used the city as a venue.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Longtime Mayor Don Plusquellic announced on May 8, 2015, that he would resign on May 31 after 28 years as mayor and 41 years of service to the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city continues to deal with the effects of air and soil pollution from its industrial past.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In the southwestern part of the city, soil was contaminated and noxious PCB-laden fumes were put into the air by an electrical transformer deconstruction operation that existed from the 1930s to the 1960s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Cleanup of the site, designated as a Superfund site by the Environmental Protection Agency, began in 1987 and concluded in 2000.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The area remains restricted with regular reviews of the site and its underground aquifer.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] City founder Simon Perkins negotiated a treaty with Native Americans to establish a mail route from the Connecticut Western Reserve to Detroit in 1807, an early example of historic humanitarian affairs in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Aside from being part of the Underground Railroad, when active, John Brown was a resident, today having two landmarks (the John Brown House and the John Brown Monument) dedicated to him.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the 1851 Women's Rights Convention, Sojourner Truth delivered her speech entitled "Ain't I A Woman?".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1905, a statue of an Indian named Unk was erected on Portage Path, which was part of the effective western boundary of the White and Native American lands from 1785 to 1805.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Summit County chapter of the Ku Klux Klan reported having 50,000 members, making it the largest local chapter in the country during the 20th century.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] At some point the sheriff, county officials, mayor of Akron, judges, county commissioners, and most members of Akron's school board were members.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Klan's influence in the city's politics eventually ended after Wendell Willkie arrived and challenged them.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Race played a part in two of Akron's major riots, the Riot of 1900 and the Wooster Ave.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Others giving speeches on race in the city include W.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Du Bois (1920) and President Bill Clinton (1997).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1971, Alpha Phi Alpha Homes Inc. was founded in Akron by the Eta Tau Lambda chapter of Alpha Phi Alpha, with James R.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The centerpiece, Henry Arthur Callis Tower, is located in the Channelwood Village area of the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2008, 91-year-old Akron native, Addie Polk, became the poster child of the Great Recession, after shooting herself.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2022, Akron resident Jayland Walker was killed by police while fleeing, sparking days of protest and the institution of a police review board.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron is located in the Great Lakes region about 39 miles (63 km) south of Lake Erie, on the Glaciated Allegheny Plateau.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It is bordered by Cuyahoga Falls on the north and Barberton in the southwest.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It is the center of the Akron metropolitan area which covers Summit and Portage Counties, and a principal city of the larger Cleveland–Akron–Canton Combined Statistical Area.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Located on the western end of the plateau, the topography of Akron includes rolling hills and varied terrain.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Ohio and Erie Canal passes through the city, separating the east from west.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has the only biogas facility in the United States that produces methane through the decomposition process of sludge to create electricity.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has a humid continental climate (Köppen *Dfa*), typical of the Midwest, with four distinct seasons, and lies in USDA hardiness zone 6b, degrading to zone 6a in the outlying suburbs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Winters are cold and dry but typically bring a mix of rain, sleet, and snow with occasional heavy snowfall and icing.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] January is the coldest month with an average mean temperature of 27.9 °F (−2.3 °C), with temperatures on average dropping to or below 0 °F (−18 °C) on 3.3 days and staying at or below freezing on 40 days per year.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Snowfall averages 47.2 inches (120 cm) per season, significantly less than the snowbelt areas closer to Lake Erie.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The snowiest month on record was 37.5 inches (95 cm) in January 1978, while winter snowfall amounts have ranged from 82.0 in (208 cm) in 1977–78 to 18.2 in (46 cm) in 1949–50.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Springs generally see a transition to fewer weather systems that produce heavier rainfall.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Summers are typically very warm and humid with temperatures at or above 90 °F (32 °C) on 10.7 days per year on average; the annual count has been as high as 36 days in 1931, while the most recent year to not reach that mark is 2023.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] July is the warmest month with an average mean temperature of 73.9 °F (23 °C).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Autumn is relatively dry with many clear warm days and cool nights.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The all-time record high temperature in Akron of 104 °F (40 °C) was established on August 6, 1918, and the all-time record low temperature of −25 °F (−32 °C) was set on January 19, 1994.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The most precipitation to fall on one calendar day was on July 7, 1943, when 5.96" of rain was measured.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The first and last freezes of the season on average fall on October 21 and April 26, respectively, allowing a growing season of 174 days.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The normal annual mean temperature is 51.7 °F (10.9 °C).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Normal yearly precipitation based on the 30-year average from 1991 to 2020 is 41.57 inches (1,056 mm), falling on an average 160 days.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Monthly precipitation has ranged from 12.55 in (319 mm) in July 2003 to 0.19 in (4.8 mm) in August 2025, while for annual precipitation the historical range is 65.70 in (1,669 mm) in 1990 to 23.79 in (604 mm) in 1963.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron consists of 21 neighborhoods, with an additional three that are unincorporated but recognized within the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The neighborhoods of the city differ in design largely because of expansions such as town merging, annexation, housing construction in various time periods, and rubber era.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Maple Valley covers the west end of Copley Road, before reaching I-77.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Along this strip are several businesses using the name, as well as the Maple Valley Branch of the Akron-Summit County Public Library.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Spicertown falls under the blanket of University Park, this term is used frequently to describe the student-centered retail and residential area around East Exchange and Spicer streets, near the University of Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] West Hill is roughly bounded by West Market Street on the north, West Exchange Street on the south, Downtown on the East, and Rhodes Avenue on the west.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It features many stately older homes, particularly in the recently recognized Oakdale Historic District.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron's suburbs include Barberton, Cuyahoga Falls, Fairlawn, Green, Hudson, Mogadore, Montrose-Ghent, Munroe Falls, Norton, Silver Lake, Stow, and Tallmadge.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron formed Joint Economic Development Districts with Springfield, Coventry, Copley, and Bath (in conjunction with Fairlawn) townships.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The population of the Akron metropolitan area was 702,219 in 2020.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron is also part of the larger Cleveland-Akron-Canton combined statistical area, which was the 15th largest in the country with a population of over 3.5 million residents.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron experienced a significant collapse in population having lost over one third (34.6%) of its population between 1960 and 2020.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Although Akron is in northern Ohio, where the Inland North dialect is expected, its settlement history puts it in the North Midland dialect area.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Some localisms that have developed include *devilstrip*, which refers to the grass strip between a sidewalk and street.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] As of the 2020 census, Akron had a population of 190,469.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] 21.4% of residents were under the age of 18 and 16.0% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.7 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.1 males age 18 and over.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while <0.1% lived in rural areas.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] There were 82,970 households in Akron, of which 25.2% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Of all households, 28.2% were married-couple households, 24.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 38.2% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] About 37.7% of all households were made up of individuals and 13.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] There were 92,517 housing units, of which 10.3% were vacant.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Among occupied housing units, 49.8% were owner-occupied and 50.2% were renter-occupied.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.0% and the rental vacancy rate was 8.7%.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] As of the census of 2010, there were 199,110 people, 83,712 households, and 47,084 families residing in the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The population density was 3,209.9 inhabitants per square mile (1,239.3/km2).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] There were 96,288 housing units at an average density of 1,552.3 per square mile (599.3/km2).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 62.2% White, 31.5% African American, 0.2% Native American, 2.1% Asian, 0.8% from other races, and 3.2% from two or more races.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 2.1% of the population.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 61.2% of the population, down from 81.0% in 1970.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] There were 83,712 households, of which 28.8% had children under age 18 living with them, 31.3% were married couples living together, 19.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.5% had a male householder with no wife present, and 43.8% were non-families.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] 34.8% of all households were made up of individuals, and 10.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The average household size was 2.31 and the average family size was 2.98.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The median age in the city was 35.7 years.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The gender makeup of the city was 48.3% male and 51.7% female.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1999, Akron ranked as the 94th-most-dangerous city (and the 229th safest) on the 7th Morgan Quitno list.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Preliminary Ohio crime statistics show aggravated assaults increased by 45% during 2007.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Historically, organized crime operated in the city with the presence of the *Black Hand* led by Rosario Borgio, once headquartered on the city's north side in the first decade of the 20th century and the *Walker-Mitchell* mob, of which Pretty Boy Floyd was a member.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has experienced several riots in its history, including the Riot of 1900 and the Wooster Avenue Riots of 1968.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The distribution of methamphetamine ("meth") in Akron greatly contributed to Summit County becoming known as the "Meth Capital of Ohio" in the early 2000s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The county ranked third in the nation in the number of registered meth sites.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the 1990s, motorcycle gang the Hells Angels sold the drug from bars frequented by members.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Between January 2004 and August 2009, the city had significantly more registered sites than any other city in the state.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Authorities believed a disruption of a major Mexican meth operation contributed to the increase of it being made locally.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2007, the Akron Police Department (APD) received a grant to help continue its work with other agencies and jurisdictions to support them in ridding the city of meth labs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The APD coordinates with the Summit County Drug Unit and the Drug Enforcement Administration, forming the Clandestine Methamphetamine Laboratory Response Team.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has won economic awards such as for City Livability and All-America City, and deemed a high tech haven greatly contributing to the Information Age.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Current Fortune 500 companies headquartered in the city include Goodyear and FirstEnergy.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In addition, the city is the headquarters to GOJO, Advanced Elastomer Systems, Babcock & Wilcox, Myers Industries, Acme Fresh Market, and Sterling Jewelers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Goodyear built a new world headquarters in the city in 2013.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Bridgestone built a new technical center with research and development labs, and moved its product development operations to the new facility in early 2012.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Eastern Ohio division of KeyBank, which has six branches in the city, built a regional headquarters downtown.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Northeast Ohio's Polymer Valley is centered in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The area holds forty-five percent of the state's polymer industries, with the oldest dating to the 19th century.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, an influx of new polymer companies came to the region.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2001, more than 400 companies manufactured polymer-based materials in the region.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Many University of Akron scientists became world-renowned for their research done at the Goodyear Polymer Center.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The first College of Polymer Science and Polymer Engineering was begun by the university.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2010, the National Polymer Innovation Center opened on campus.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has designated an area called the Biomedical Corridor, aimed at luring health-related ventures to the region.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It encompasses 1,240 acres (5.0 km2) of private and publicly owned land, bounded by Akron General on the west and Akron City on the east, and also includes Akron Children's near the district's center with the former Saint Thomas Hospital to the north of its northern boundaries.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Since its start in 2006, the corridor added the headquarters of companies such as Akron Polymer Systems.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron's adult hospitals are owned by two health systems, Summa Health System and Akron General Health System.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Summa Health System operates Summa Akron City Hospital and the former St.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Thomas Hospital, which in 2008 were recognized for the 11th consecutive year as one of "America's Best Hospitals" by U.S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Summa is recognized as having one of the best orthopaedics programs in the nation with a ranking of 28th.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron General Health in affiliation with the Cleveland Clinic operates Akron General Medical Center, which in 2009, was recognized as one of "America's Best Hospitals" by U.S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron Children's Hospital is an independent entity that specializes in pediatric care and burn care.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 1974, Howard Igel and Aaron Freeman successfully grew human skin in a lab to treat burn victims, making Akron Children's Hospital the first hospital in the world to achieve such a feat.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron City and Akron General hospitals are designated Level I Trauma Centers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Thomas Hall, one of three Akron performance halls.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Regular acts include the Akron Symphony Orchestra, Tuesday Musical Club, and Children's Concert Society.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] World-class performance events include Broadway musicals, ballets, comedies, lectures, and entertainers attracting 400,000 visitors annually.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The hall seats 2,955, divided among three tiers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Located downtown is the Akron Civic Theatre, a movie palace which opened in 1929 and contains many Moorish features, including arches and decorative tiles.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Lock 3, a historic Ohio and Erie Canalway landmark, has been transformed into an entertainment amphitheater that hosts festivals, concerts, and community events throughout the year.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In Highland Square, Akron hosts a convergence of art, music, and community annually called Art in the Square, a festival featuring local artists and musicians.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The downtown Akron Art Museum features art produced since 1850 along with national and international exhibitions.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It opened in 1922 as the Akron Art Institute, in the basement of the Akron Public Library.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It moved to its current location at the renovated 1899 post office building in 1981.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2007, the museum more than tripled in size with the addition of the John S. and James L.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Knight Building, which received the 2005 American Architecture Award from the Chicago Athenaeum while still under construction.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron Zoo is located just outside downtown and was an initial gift of property from the city's founding family.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Built between 1912 and 1915 for Goodyear Tire & Rubber co-founder Frank Seiberling, Stan Hywet Hall and Gardens is the seventh-largest historic house in the United States.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It hosts various attractions and public events throughout the year.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron is home to the American Marble and Toy Museum.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] National events hosted annually in Akron cover a wide variety of hobbies and interests.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The PGA World Golf Championships travel to Akron each year for the Bridgestone Invitational at Firestone Country Club.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The All-American Soap Box Derby is a youth racing program which has its World Championship finals at Derby Downs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In mid July, the National Hamburger Festival consists of different vendors serving original recipe hamburgers and has a Miss Hamburger contest.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Lock 3 Park annually hosts the First Night Akron celebration on New Year's Eve.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The park also annually hosts the Italian Festival and the "Rib, White & Blue" food festival in July.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Founders Day is celebrated annually because of the founding of Alcoholics Anonymous within the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] As a result of multiple towns merging, and industry boom, Akron's architecture is diverse.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Originally a canal town, the city is divided into two parts by the Ohio and Erie Canal, with downtown being centered on it.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Along the locks, the city has a path paved with rubber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The contrasting neighborhoods of Goodyear Heights and Firestone Park were built during the rubber industry to house workers and their families.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Both are communities filled with houses based on mail-order plans.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2009, the National Arbor Day Foundation designated Akron as a Tree City USA for the 14th time.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Many of the city's government and civic buildings, including City Hall and the Summit County Courthouse are from pre-World War Two, but the Akron-Summit County Public Library, and John S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The library originally opened in 1969, but reopened as a greatly expanded facility in 2004.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The First Methodist Episcopal Church first used the Akron Plan in 1872.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The plan later gained popularity, being used in many Congregationalist, Baptist, and Presbyterian church buildings.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Completed in 1931, Akron's tallest building, the Huntington Tower features the art deco style and is covered in glazed architectural terra-cotta.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Standing 330 feet (100 m) tall, it is built on top of the Hamilton Building, completed in 1900 in the neo-Gothic style.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Near the turn of the millennium the tower was given a $2.5 million facelift, including a $1.8 million restoration of the tower's terra-cotta, brick, and limestone.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The top of the building has a television broadcast tower formerly used by WAKR-TV (now WVPX-TV) and WAKR-AM.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Located on the University of Akron campus, the Goodyear Polymer Center consists of glass twin towers connected by walkways.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The university also formerly used the old Quaker Oats factory as a dormitory, including using it as a quarantine center during the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] For many years it had been a shopping center called Quaker Square.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron Art Museum commissioned Coop Himmelblau to design an expansion in 2007.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The new building connects to the old building and is divided into three parts known as the "Crystal", the "Gallery Box", and the "Roof Cloud".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron is home to the 70 acre National Historic Landmark Stan Hywet Hall and Gardens, a historic steel frame house and gardens that includes the seventh-largest house in the United States, was the home of Frank Seiberling, co-founder of the Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company, and is now a museum.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Several residents of Akron have played a role in defining American cuisine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Ferdinand Schumacher created the first American oatmeal and is a pioneer of breakfast cereal.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] He also founded the Empire Barley Mill and German Mills American Oatmeal Company, which would later merge several times with other companies, with the result being the Quaker Oats Company.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Menches Brothers, are the disputed inventors of the waffle ice cream cone, caramel corn, and hamburger.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Strickland's Frozen Custard is located in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron RubberDucks baseball team moved to Akron from Canton in 1997 and have won the Eastern League Championship six times, most recently in 2021.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron Marathon is an annual marathon in the city which offers a team relay and shorter races throughout the summer and fall.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The All-American Soap Box Derby takes place each year at the Derby Downs since 1936.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] LeBron James' King for Kids bike-a-thon feature James riding with kids through the city each June.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In November, the city hosts the annual Home Run for the Homeless 4-mile run.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron hosted some of the events of the 2014 Gay Games including the marathon, the men's and women's golf tournaments at Firestone Country Club, and softball at Firestone Stadium.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The University of Akron's Akron Zips compete in the NCAA and the Mid-American Conference (MAC) in a variety of sports at the Division I level.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The men's basketball team appeared in the NCAA Tournament in 1986, 2009, 2011, and 2013.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In 2009, the Zips men's soccer team completed the regular-season undefeated, then won the NCAA Men's Division I Soccer Championship in 2010.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Zippy, one of the eight female NCAA mascots, won the National Mascot of the Year contest in 2007.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron had 2 teams who won the National Basketball League in the '30s and '40s, before the foundation of the NBA.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Firestone Country Club, which annually hosted the WGC-Bridgestone Invitational, has in the past hosted the PGA Championship, American Golf Classic, and Rubber City Open Invitational.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] On January 7, 1938, Akron became the birthplace of women's professional Mud Wrestling, in a match including Professional Wrestling, WWE, and Wrestling Observer Hall of Famer, Mildred Burke.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Professional Bowlers Association started in the city during 1958.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Summit Metro Parks is the metroparks system serving Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Major parks in Akron include Lock 3, Firestone, Goodyear Heights, the F.A.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Seiberling Nature Realm, and part of Cuyahoga Valley National Park.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Located within the Sand Run Metro Park, the 104 acres (0.42 km2) F.A.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Seiberling Nature Realm features a visitor center, hiking trails, three ponds, gardens, and an array of special programs throughout the year.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron Police Museum displays mementos including items from Pretty Boy Floyd, whose gang frequented the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Several of the parks are along the locks of the Ohio and Erie Canal.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Lock 3 Park in downtown Akron features an outdoor amphitheater hosting live music, festivals and special events year-round.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The park was created in the early 21st century to provide green space within the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In the winter, the park is temporarily converted into an outdoor ice-skating rink.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Adjacent to the Derby Downs race hill is a 19,000-square-foot (1,800 m2) outdoor skatepark, and nearby is a BMX racing course where organized races are often held in the warmer months.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron residents can enjoy various ice skating activities year-round at the historic Akron Ice House.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Ohio and Erie Canal Towpath Trail is a regional bike and hike trail that follows the canal north to Cleveland and south to New Philadelphia, Ohio.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The trail features a floating observation deck section over Summit Lake.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] It is a popular tourist attraction, as it attracts over 2 million visits annually.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Portage Hike and Bike Trail connects with the hike and bike trails in the county.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The mayor of Akron is elected in a citywide vote.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The current mayor is Shammas Malik, who succeeded Dan Horrigan after the 2023 election.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city is divided into 10 wards, each elect a member to the Akron City Council, while an additional 3 are elected at large.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The mayor's cabinet currently consists of directors and deputy directors of administration, communications, community relations, economic development, intergovernmental relations, labor relations, law, planning & urban development, planning director – deputy, public safety, and public service.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city adopted a new charter of the commissioner manager type in 1920, but reverted to its old form in 1924.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Ohio Ninth District Court of Appeals is based in the city, as is one of four courthouses of the United States District Court for the Northern District of Ohio.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Preschool, elementary, and secondary education is mainly provided by the Akron City School District.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The district's planning began in 1840 when Ansel Miller proposed building free public schools for all children, funded by property taxes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] After facing opposition, Miller teamed up with Isaac Jennings, who became chair of a committee to improve the school system.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] On November 21, 1846, their plan was unanimously approved by citizens, and the Ohio Legislature adopted it as "An Act for the Support and Better Regulation of the Common Schools of the Town of Akron" on February 8, 1847.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron's first public schools opened in the fall of 1847 and were led by Mortimer Leggett. he first annual report showed that it cost less than $2 a year to educate a child.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Primary schools were taught by young women, who were paid less and supervised by a male superintendent.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] From 1877 to 1952, Akron graduated students semi-annually instead of annually.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In the 1920s, an Americanization program was designed to help the many Akron students who were first-generation Americans.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] All Akron public schools are going through a 15-year, $800 million rebuilding process.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city's schools have been moved from "Academic Watch" to "Continuous Improvement" by the Ohio Department of Education.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron also has many private, parochial and charter schools.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] As part of his charitable foundation's initiatives in the city, LeBron James founded the I Promise School, which serves underprivileged kids.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron was served by the Akron Digital Academy from 2002 to 2018, when it shut down.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city is home to the University of Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Originally Buchtel College, the school is home of the Goodyear Polymer Center and the National Polymer Innovation Center.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Part of the University System of Ohio, the university enrolls approximately 15,000 students.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron was served in print by the daily *Akron Beacon Journal,* formerly the flagship newspaper of the Knight Newspapers chain; the weekly "The Akron Reporter"; and the weekly *West Side Leader* newspapers and the monthly magazine *Akron Life*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] *The Buchtelite* newspaper is published by the University of Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron is part of the Cleveland-Akron-Canton TV market, the 18th largest market in the U.S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Within the market, WEAO (PBS), WVPX (ION), and WBNX-TV (The CW) are licensed to Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] WEAO serves Akron specifically, while WBNX and WVPX identify as "Akron/Cleveland", serving the entire market.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has no native news broadcast, having lost its only news station when the former WAKC became WVPX in 1996.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] WVPX and Cleveland's WKYC later provided a joint news program, which was cancelled in 2005.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Though it is part of a combined TV market with Cleveland, Akron is its own radio market, with 11 stations directly serving it, including music stations WQMX 94.9 (Country), WONE 97.5 (Classic rock), WKDD 98.1 (Contemporary Hits), and WAKR 1590/93.5 (Classic hits/Full service).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] WHLO 640 and WNIR-FM 100.1 feature news/talk formats, while WKJA 91.9 airs religious programming.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] As the regional NPR affiliate, WKSU 89.7 serves all of Northeast Ohio (including both the Cleveland and Akron markets).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron has served as the setting for several major studio and independent films.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Inducted into the National Film Registry, *Dance, Girl, Dance* (1940), tells the story of two dancers from Akron who go to New York City.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] *My Name is Bill W.* (1989) tells the true story of Bill Wilson who co-founded Alcoholics Anonymous, which held its first meetings at the Stan Hywet Hall and Gardens and has over two million members today.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The program's connection to the Saint Thomas Hospital is alluded to in an episode of the television series *Prison Break* (2005), where Michael Scofield talks to Sara Tancredi on the phone while there.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The Akron Armory is used as a venue for a female wrestling team in *...All the Marbles* (1981).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] *More than a Game* (2009) documents National Basketball Association player LeBron James and his St.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Mary High School high school basketball team's journey.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] In Drake's music video to *Forever* (2009) off the *More than a Game* soundtrack (2009), the iconic Goodyear's logo on top the company's theater is shown.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The city has been frequently portrayed in media, from "Hell on Earth" in the television series *I'm In Hell* (2007), to the whereabouts of a holy woman in *The Virgin of Akron, Ohio* (2007).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Henry Spivey of *My Own Worst Enemy* (2008), travels to Akron through the series many times.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] George Costanza in an episode of *Seinfeld* (1989), flies to Akron and has a meeting at Firestone.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] *M.Y.O.B.* (2008) is centered on an Akron runaway girl named Riley Veatch.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Jake Foley of *Jake 2.0* (2003), Pickles family of the *Rugrats* (1991), and J.Reid of *In Too Deep* (1999), and Avery Barkley of Nashville (2016) are also from the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] Akron was also in the spotlight on the television show Criminal Minds "Compromising Positions" (2010) Season 6, Episode 4.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p01] The 2015 film *Room* is set in Akron, filmed in Toronto with staging to signify Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The primary terminal that airline passengers traveling to or from Akron use is the Akron–Canton Airport, serving nearly 2 million passengers a year.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The Akron-Canton Airport is a commercial Class C airport located in the suburb of Green, Ohio, roughly 10 mi (16 km) southeast of Akron operated jointly by Stark and Summit counties.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] It serves as an alternative for travelers to or from the Cleveland area as well.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Akron Fulton International Airport is a general aviation airport located in and owned by the city that serves private planes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] It first opened in 1929 and has operated in several different capacities since then.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The airport had commercial scheduled airline service until the 1950s and it is now used for both cargo and private planes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] It is home of the Lockheed Martin Airdock, where the Goodyear airships, dirigibles, and blimps were originally stored and maintained.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The Goodyear blimps are now housed outside of Akron in a facility on the shores of Wingfoot Lake in nearby Suffield Township.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Akron Northside Station is a train station at 27 Ridge Street along the Cuyahoga Valley Scenic Railroad.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Because of the city's large rubber industry, Akron was once served by a variety of railroads that competed for the city's freight and passenger business.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The largest were the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, Erie Railroad, and the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Smaller regional railroads included the Akron, Canton, and Youngstown Railroad, Northern Ohio Railway, and the Akron Barberton Belt Railroad.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Today, the city is served by CSX Corporation, the Wheeling & Lake Erie Railroad, and their subsidiary Akron-Barberton-Cluster, which operate out of the W&LE's Akron Yard near Brittain Road on the eastern end of the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] From 1891 to 1971 passenger service to points throughout the Midwest, as well as Washington and New York City, was provided at Akron Union Station.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The last legacy passenger trains were the Erie Lackawanna's *Lake Cities* (ended, 1970) and the B&O's *Shenandoah* (ended, 1971).
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] There is currently no passenger rail transportation with the elimination of Amtrak's former *Three Rivers* service in 2005.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The nearest Amtrak service is in Alliance, Ohio or Cleveland.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Public transportation is available through the METRO Regional Transit Authority system, whose fleet of over 200 buses and trolleys operates local routes and commuter buses into downtown Cleveland.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Stark Area Regional Transit Authority (SARTA) also has a bus line running between Canton and Akron and the Portage Area Regional Transportation Authority (PARTA) runs an express route connecting the University of Akron with Kent State University.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Pfaff Transit Center on South Broadway Street.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] This facility, which opened in 2009, also houses inter-city bus transportation available through Greyhound Lines.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Akron is served by two major interstate highways that bisect the city.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Unlike other cities, the bisection does not occur in the Central Business District, nor do the interstates serve downtown; rather, the Akron Innerbelt and to a lesser extent Ohio State Route 8 serve these functions.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Akron has produced and been home to a number of notable individuals in varying fields.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Its natives and residents are called "Akronites".
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The first postmaster of the Connecticut Western Reserve and president of its bank, General Simon Perkins (1771–1844), co-founded Akron in 1825.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] His son, Colonel Simon Perkins (1805–1877), while living in Akron during the same time as abolitionist John Brown (1800–1859), went into business with Brown.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Wendell Willkie, the Republican nominee for president in 1940, worked in Akron as a lawyer for Firestone.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Pioneering televangelist Rex Humbard rose to prominence in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Knight ran the national Knight Newspapers chain from Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Broadcaster Hugh Downs was born in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] In the mid- to late 1940s, pioneering rock 'n' roll DJ Alan Freed was musical director at Akron's WAKR.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Watergate figure John Dean was born in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Former NFL linebacker James Harrison was born in Akron, as was former Tennessee Titans head coach and current New England Patriots Head Coach, Mike Vrabel.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Clayton Murphy, professional middle-distance runner and 2016 Olympic Games bronze medalist, competed in cross country and track & field for the Akron Zips.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Clark Gable and John Lithgow also lived in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Poet Rita Dove was born and grew up in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] She went on to become the first African-American United States Poet Laureate.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Many of her poems are about or take place in Akron, foremost among them *Thomas and Beulah*, which earned her the 1987 Pulitzer Prize for Poetry.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Owner of over 400 patents, native Stanford R.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Ovshinsky invented the widely used nickel-metal hydride battery.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Richard Smalley, winner of a Nobel Prize in Chemistry for discovering buckminsterfullerene (buckyballs) was born in the city during 1943.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Another native, the second U.S. female astronaut in space, Judith Resnik, died in the 1986 Space Shuttle *Challenger* disaster and has the Resnik Moon crater named in her honor.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The Silver Screen, which came to symbolize Hollywood's movie entertainment industry, was invented by Kenmore resident and projectionist Harry Coulter Williams.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] First used in Akron's Majestic Theater and then Norka Theater, the "Williams Perlite" tear-proof, vinyl plastic indoor motion picture screen was installed in all the major movie houses, including the rapidly expanding theaters built by Warner Bros. of nearby Youngstown OH.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Williams' unique silver-painted screens were adapted for CinemaScope, VistaVision, and later 3-D movies.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] They provided a brighter picture at all angles with top reflectivity at direct viewing and extra diffusion for side seats and balconies.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] Carol Folt, the 11th chancellor and 29th chief executive, of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill was born in Akron in 1951.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] She was previously provost (chief academic officer) and interim president of Dartmouth College.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] She assumed her duties on July 1, 2013, and is the first woman to lead UNC.
[src:babcock-wilcox/akron-ohio-p02] The philosopher and logician Willard van Orman Quine was born and grew up in Akron.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] There are six types, all of which are composed of long and thin fibrous crystals, with each fibre (particulate with length substantially greater than width) composed of many microscopic "fibrils" that can be released into the atmosphere by abrasion and other processes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Inhalation of asbestos fibres can lead to various dangerous lung conditions, including mesothelioma, asbestosis, and lung cancer.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] As a result of these health effects, asbestos is considered a serious health and safety hazard.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Archaeological studies have found evidence of asbestos being used as far back as the Stone Age to strengthen ceramic pots, but large-scale mining began at the end of the 19th century when manufacturers and builders began using asbestos for its desirable physical properties.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Many buildings constructed before the 1980s contain asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of asbestos for construction and fireproofing has been made illegal in many countries.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Despite this, around 255,000 people are thought to die each year from diseases related to asbestos exposure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In part, this is because many older buildings still contain asbestos; in addition, the consequences of exposure can take decades to arise.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The latency period (from exposure until the diagnosis of negative health effects) is typically 20 years.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The most common diseases associated with chronic asbestos exposure are asbestosis (scarring of the lungs due to asbestos inhalation) and mesothelioma (a type of cancer).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Many developing countries still use asbestos as a building material, and asbestos mining continues, with the top producer, Russia, producing an estimated 790,000 tonnes in 2020.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The word "asbestos", first used in the 1600s, ultimately derives from the Ancient Greek: ἄσβεστος, meaning "unquenchable" or "inextinguishable".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The name reflects use of the substance for wicks that would never burn up.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It was adopted into English via the Old French *abestos*, which derived the word from Greek via Latin, but in the original Greek, "asbestos" actually referred to quicklime.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It is said by the Oxford English Dictionary that the word was wrongly used by Pliny the Elder for what is now called asbestos, and that he popularized the misnomer.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos was originally referred to in Greek as *amiantos*, meaning "undefiled", because when thrown into a fire it came out unmarked.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] "Amiantos" is the source for the word for asbestos in many languages, such as the Portuguese, the Spanish, and the Italian *amianto* and the French *amiante*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It had also been called "amiant" in English in the early 15th century, but this usage was superseded by "asbestos".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The word is pronounced /æsˈbɛstəs/ or /æsˈbɛstɒs/.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos has been used for thousands of years to create flexible objects that resist fire, such as napkins and other textiles.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Mass production of asbestos-containing consumer goods began in the modern era.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Today, the risk of asbestos has been recognized; the use of asbestos is completely banned in 66 countries and strictly regulated in many others.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos use dates back at least 4,500 years, when the inhabitants of the Lake Juojärvi region in East Finland strengthened earthenware pots and cooking utensils with the asbestos mineral anthophyllite; archaeologists call this style of pottery "asbestos-ceramic".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some archaeologists believe that ancient peoples made shrouds of asbestos, wherein they burned the bodies of their kings to preserve only their ashes and to prevent the ashes being mixed with those of wood or other combustible materials commonly used in funeral pyres.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Others assert that these peoples used asbestos to make perpetual wicks for sepulchral or other lamps.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] A famous example is the golden lamp *asbestos lychnis*, which the sculptor Callimachus made for the Erechtheion.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In more recent centuries, asbestos was indeed used for this purpose.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] A once-purported first description of asbestos occurs in Theophrastus, *On Stones*, from around 300 BC, but this identification has been refuted.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In both modern and ancient Greek, the usual name for the material known in English as "asbestos" is *amiantos* ("undefiled", "pure"), which was adapted into the French as *amiante* and into Italian, Spanish and Portuguese as *amianto*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In modern Greek, the word ἀσβεστος or ασβέστης stands consistently and solely for lime.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The term *asbestos* is traceable to Roman naturalist Pliny the Elder's first-century manuscript *Natural History* and his use of the term *asbestinon*, meaning "unquenchable"; he described the mineral as being more expensive than pearls.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] While Pliny or his nephew Pliny the Younger is popularly credited with recognising the detrimental effects of asbestos on human beings, examination of the primary sources reveals no support for either claim.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In China, accounts of obtaining *huǒ huàn bù* (火浣布) or "fire-laundered cloth" certainly date to the Wei dynasty (386-535 AD), and there are claims they were known as early as in the Zhou dynasty, though not substantiated except in writings thought to date much later (see *huoshu* or "fire rat").
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Athanasius of Alexandria, a Christian bishop living in 4th-century Egypt, references asbestos in one of his writings.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Wealthy Persians amazed guests by cleaning a cloth by exposing it to fire.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] For example, according to Tabari, one of the curious items belonging to Khosrow II Parviz, the great Sassanian king (r.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] 590–628), was a napkin (Persian: منديل) that he cleaned simply by throwing it into the fire.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Such cloth is believed to have been made of asbestos imported over the Hindu Kush.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] According to Biruni in his book *Gems*, any cloths made of asbestos (Persian: آذرشست, *āzarshost*) were called *shostakeh* (Persian: شستكه).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some Persians believed the fiber was the fur of an animal called the *samandar* (Persian: سمندر), which lived in fire and died when exposed to water; this was where the former belief originated that the salamander could tolerate fire.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Charlemagne, the first Holy Roman Emperor (800–814), is also said to have possessed such a tablecloth.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The large-scale asbestos industry began in the mid-19th century.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Early attempts at producing asbestos paper and cloth in Italy began in the 1850s but failed to create a market for these products.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Canadian asbestos samples were displayed in London in 1862, and the first companies were formed in England and Scotland to exploit this resource.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos was first used in the manufacture of yarn, and German industrialist Louis Wertheim adopted this process in his factories in Germany.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 1871, the Patent Asbestos Manufacturing Company was established in Glasgow, and during the following decades, the Clydebank area became a centre for the nascent industry.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Industrial-scale mining began in the Thetford Hills, Quebec, from the 1870s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Sir William Edmond Logan was the first to notice the large deposits of chrysotile in the hills in his capacity as head of Geological Survey of Canada.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Samples of the minerals from there were displayed in London and elicited much interest.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] With the opening of the Quebec Central Railway in 1876, mining entrepreneurs such as Andrew Stuart Johnson and William Henry Jeffrey established the asbestos industry in the province.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The 50-ton output of the mines in 1878 rose to over 10,000 tonnes in the 1890s with the adoption of machine technologies and expanded production.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] For a long time, the world's largest asbestos mine was the Jeffrey Mine in the town of Asbestos, Quebec.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos production began in the Urals of the Russian Empire in the 1880s, and the Alpine regions of Northern Italy with the formation in Turin of the Italo-English Pure Asbestos Company in 1876, although the greater production levels from the Canadian mines soon overtook European production.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Mining also took off in South Africa from 1893 under the aegis of the British businessman Francis Oates, the director of the De Beers company.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It was in South Africa that the production of amosite began in 1910.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The US asbestos industry began in 1858 when fibrous anthophyllite was mined for use as asbestos insulation by the Johns Company, a predecessor to the current Johns Manville, at a quarry at Ward's Hill on Staten Island, New York.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] US production began in earnest in 1899 with the discovery of large deposits in Belvidere Mountain in Vermont.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2011, it was reported that over 50% of UK houses still contained asbestos, despite a ban on asbestos products some years earlier.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In Japan, particularly after World War II, asbestos was used in the manufacture of ammonium sulfate for purposes of rice production, sprayed upon the ceilings, iron skeletons, and walls of railroad cars and buildings (during the 1960s), and used for energy efficiency reasons as well.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos production in Japan peaked in 1974 and fluctuated until about 1990, when production began to drop dramatically.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The 1898 Annual Report of the Chief Inspector of Factories and Workshops in the United Kingdom noted the negative health effects of asbestos, the contribution having been made by Lucy Deane Streatfeild, one of the first women factory inspectors.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Montague Murray noted the negative health effects of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The first documented death related to asbestos was in 1906.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the early 1900s, researchers began to notice a large number of early deaths and lung problems in asbestos-mining towns.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The first such study was conducted by Murray at the Charing Cross Hospital, London, in 1900, in which a postmortem investigation discovered asbestos traces in the lungs of a young man who had died from pulmonary fibrosis after having worked for 14 years in an asbestos textile factory.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Adelaide Anderson, the Inspector of Factories in Britain, included asbestos in a list of harmful industrial substances in 1902.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Similar investigations were conducted in France in 1906 and Italy in 1908.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The first diagnosis of asbestosis was made in the UK in 1924.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Nellie Kershaw was employed at Turner Brothers Asbestos in Rochdale, Greater Manchester, England, from 1917, spinning raw asbestos fibre into yarn.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Her death in 1924 led to a formal inquest.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] As a result of Cooke's paper, Parliament commissioned an inquiry into the effects of asbestos dust by E.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Merewether, Medical Inspector of Factories, and C.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Price, a factory inspector and pioneer of dust monitoring and control.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Their subsequent report, *Occurrence of Pulmonary Fibrosis & Other Pulmonary Affections in Asbestos Workers*, was presented to Parliament on 24 March 1930.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It concluded that the development of asbestosis was irrefutably linked to the prolonged inhalation of asbestos dust, and included the first health study of asbestos workers, which found that 66% of those employed for 20 years or more suffered from asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The report led to the publication of the first asbestos industry regulations in 1931, which came into effect on 1 March 1932.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] These rules regulated ventilation and made asbestosis an excusable work-related disease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The term *mesothelioma* was first used in medical literature in 1931; its association with asbestos was first noted sometime in the 1940s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Similar legislation followed in the US about ten years later.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Approximately 100,000 people in the United States have died or are experiencing terminal illnesses as a result of asbestos exposure related to shipbuilding.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the Hampton Roads area, a shipbuilding center, mesothelioma occurrence is seven times the national rate.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Thousands of tons of asbestos were used in World War II ships to insulate piping, boilers, steam engines, and steam turbines.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] There were approximately 4.3 million shipyard workers in the United States during the war; for every 1,000 workers, about 14 died of mesothelioma and an unknown number died of asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The United States government and the asbestos industry have been criticized for not acting quickly enough to inform the public of dangers and to reduce public exposure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the late 1970s, court documents established that asbestos industry officials knew asbestos was dangerous since the 1930s and had concealed this fact from the public.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In Australia, asbestos was widely used in construction and other industries between 1946 and 1980.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] From the 1970s, there was increasing concern about the dangers of asbestos, and following community and union campaigning, its use was phased out, with mining having ceased in 1983.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of asbestos was phased out in 1989 and banned entirely in December 2003.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The dangers of asbestos are now well known in Australia, and there is help and support for those suffering from asbestosis or mesothelioma.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The EPA defines six mineral types as "asbestos," including those in the serpentine and amphibole classes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] All six asbestos mineral types are known to be human carcinogens.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The visible fibers are themselves each composed of millions of microscopic "fibrils" that can be released by abrasion and other processes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] "Mountain leather" is an old-fashioned term for flexible, sheet-like natural formations of asbestiform minerals which resemble leather.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos-containing minerals known to form mountain leather include: actinolite, sepiolite, and tremolite.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Artificial Christmas snow, known as flocking, was previously made with asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It was used as an effect in films including the scarecrows costume in *The Wizard of Oz*; there is a rumor that it was used as snow in the poppy field, but it was actually gypsum.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Serpentine minerals have a sheet or layered structure and produce curly fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] 12001-29-5 , is the only asbestos serpentine fiber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It is obtained from serpentinite rocks, which are common throughout the world.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Its idealized chemical formula is Mg3(Si2O5)(OH)4.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Chrysotile appears under the microscope as a white fiber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Chrysotile has been used more than any other type and was the type most commonly used in the United States.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] According to the US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Asbestos Building Inspectors Manual, chrysotile accounts for about 95% of the asbestos found in buildings in America.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Chrysotile is more flexible than amphibole asbestos and can be spun and woven into fabric.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The most common use was corrugated asbestos cement roofing, primarily for outbuildings, warehouses, and garages.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It may also be found in sheets or panels used for ceilings and sometimes for walls and floors.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Chrysotile has been a component in joint compound and some plasters.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Numerous other items have been made containing chrysotile, including brake linings, fire barriers in fuse boxes, pipe insulation, floor tiles, residential shingles, and gaskets for high-temperature equipment.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the European Union and Australia, it has been banned as a potential health hazard and is no longer used at all.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Amosite, crocidolite, tremolite, anthophyllite and actinolite are members of the amphibole class.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Amphiboles, including amosite (brown asbestos) and crocidolite (blue asbestos), were formerly used in many products until the early 1980s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Tremolite asbestos constituted a contaminant of many, if not all, naturally occurring chrysotile deposits.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of all types of asbestos in the amphibole group was banned in much of the Western world by the mid-1980s, and in Japan by 1995.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Cigarette manufacturer Lorillard (Kent's filtered cigarette) used crocidolite asbestos in its "Micronite" filter from 1952 to 1956.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] While mostly chrysotile asbestos fibers were once used in automobile brake pads, shoes, and clutch discs, amphibole contaminants were present.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Since approximately the mid-1990s, brake pads, new or replacement, have been manufactured with linings made of ceramic, carbon, metallic, and aramid fiber (Twaron or Kevlar—the same material used in bulletproof vests).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] 12172-73-5 , often referred to as brown asbestos, is a trade name for the amphiboles belonging to the cummingtonite-grunerite solid solution series, commonly from South Africa, named as a partial acronym for "Asbestos Mines of South Africa".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] One formula given for amosite is Fe7Si8O22(OH)2.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Amosite is seen under a microscope as a grey-white vitreous fiber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It is most frequently used as a fire retardant in thermal insulation products, asbestos insulating board and ceiling tiles.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] 12001-28-4 , commonly known as blue asbestos, is the fibrous form of the amphibole riebeckite, found primarily in southern Africa, but also in Australia and Bolivia.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] One formula given for crocidolite is Na2FeII3FeIII2Si8O22(OH)2.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Crocidolite is seen under a microscope as a blue fiber.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Crocidolite commonly occurs as soft friable fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestiform amphibole may also occur as soft friable fibers, but some varieties, such as amosite, are commonly straighter.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] All forms of asbestos are fibrillar in that they are composed of fibers with breadths less than 1 micrometer in bundles of very great widths.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos with particularly fine fibers is also referred to as "amianthus".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Other regulated asbestos minerals, such as tremolite asbestos, CAS No.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] 77536-67-5 , (Mg,FeII)7Si8O22(OH)2; are less commonly used industrially but can still be found in a variety of construction materials and insulation materials and have been used in a few consumer products.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Other natural asbestiform minerals, such as richterite, Na(CaNa)(Mg,FeII)5(Si8O22)(OH)2, and winchite, (CaNa)Mg4(Al,FeIII)(Si8O22)(OH)2, though not regulated, are said by some to be no less harmful than tremolite, amosite, or crocidolite.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] They are termed "asbestiform" rather than asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Although the US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has not included them in the asbestos standard, NIOSH and the American Thoracic Society have recommended them for inclusion as regulated materials because they may also be hazardous to health.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The potential for the use of asbestos to mitigate climate change has been raised.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Although the adverse aspects of mining minerals, including health effects, must be taken into account, exploration of the use of mineral wastes to sequester carbon is being studied.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of mining waste materials from nickel, copper, diamond, and platinum mines has the potential as well, but asbestos may have the greatest potential and is the subject of research now in progress in an emerging field of scientific study to examine it.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The most common type of asbestos, chrysotile, chemically reacts with carbon dioxide to produce ecologically stable magnesium carbonate.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Chrysotile, like all types of asbestos, has a large surface area that provides more places for chemical reactions to occur, compared to most other naturally occurring materials.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of asbestos in new construction projects has been banned for health and safety reasons in many developed countries or regions, including the European Union, the United Kingdom, Australia, Hong Kong, Japan, and New Zealand.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] A notable exception is the United States, where asbestos continues to be used in construction, such as cement asbestos pipes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The 5th Circuit Court prevented the EPA from banning asbestos in 1991 because EPA research showed the ban would cost between US$450 and 800 million while only saving around 200 lives in a 13-year timeframe, and that the EPA did not provide adequate evidence for the safety of alternative products.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Until the mid-1980s, small amounts of white asbestos were used in the manufacture of Artex, a decorative stipple finish, however, some of the lesser-known suppliers of Artex-type materials were still adding white asbestos until 1999.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Before the ban, asbestos was widely used in the construction industry in thousands of materials.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some are judged to be more dangerous than others due to the amount of asbestos and the material's friable nature.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Loose fill asbestos, sprayed coatings, pipe insulation, and Asbestos Insulating Board (AIB) are thought to be the most dangerous due to their high content of asbestos and friable nature.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Many older buildings built before the late 1990s contain asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the United States, there is a minimum standard for asbestos surveys as described by ASTM standard E 2356–18.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the UK, the Health and Safety Executive have issued guidance called HSG264 describing how surveys should be completed although other methods can be used if they can demonstrate they have met the regulations by other means.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The EPA includes some, but not all, asbestos-contaminated facilities on the Superfund National Priorities List (NPL).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Renovation and demolition of asbestos-contaminated buildings are subject to EPA NESHAP and OSHA Regulations.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos is not a material covered under CERCLA's innocent purchaser defense.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the UK, the removal and disposal of asbestos and substances containing it are covered by the Control of Asbestos Regulations 2006.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] US asbestos consumption hit a peak of 804,000 tons in 1973; world asbestos demand peaked around 1977, with 25 countries producing nearly 4.8 million metric tons annually.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In older buildings (e.g., those built before 1999 in the UK, before white asbestos was banned), asbestos may still be present in some areas.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Being aware of asbestos locations reduces the risk of disturbing asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Removal of asbestos building components can also remove the fire protection they provide; therefore, fire protection substitutes are required for the proper fire protection that the asbestos originally provided.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some countries, such as India, Indonesia, China, and Russia, have continued widespread use of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The most common is corrugated asbestos-cement sheets or "A/C sheets" for roofing and sidewalls.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Millions of homes, factories, schools, or sheds, and shelters continue to use asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Cutting these sheets to size and drilling holes to receive 'J' bolts to help secure the sheets to roof framing is done on-site.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] There has been no significant change in production and use of A/C sheets in developing countries following the widespread restrictions in developed nations.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] As New York City's World Trade Center collapsed following the September 11 attacks, Lower Manhattan was blanketed in a mixture of building debris and combustible materials.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] This complex mixture gave rise to the concern that thousands of residents and workers in the area would be exposed to known hazards in the air and dust, such as asbestos, lead, glass fibers, and pulverized concrete.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] More than 1,000 tons of asbestos are thought to have been released into the air following the buildings' destruction.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Monitoring at and near Ground Zero immediately after the attacks indicated that the dust contained fibers, including various forms of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Inhalation of a mixture of asbestos and other toxicants is thought to be linked to the unusually high death rate from cancer of emergency service workers since the disaster.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Thousands more are now thought to be at risk of developing cancer due to this exposure, with those who have died so far being only the "tip of the iceberg".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Vermiculite is a hydrated laminar magnesium-aluminum-iron silicate that resembles mica.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It can be used for many industrial applications and has been used as insulation.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some deposits of vermiculite are contaminated with small amounts of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Grace and Company in Libby, Montana exposed workers and community residents to danger by mining vermiculite contaminated with asbestos, typically richterite, winchite, actinolite or tremolite.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Vermiculite contaminated with asbestos from the Libby mine was used as insulation in residential and commercial buildings through Canada and the United States.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Grace and Company's loose-fill vermiculite was marketed as Zonolite but was also used in sprayed-on products such as Monokote.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 1999, the EPA began cleanup efforts in Libby, and now the area is a Superfund cleanup area.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The EPA has determined that harmful asbestos is released from the mine as well as through other activities that disturb soil in the area.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Talc can sometimes be contaminated with asbestos due to the proximity of asbestos ore (usually tremolite) in underground talc deposits.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] By 1973, US federal law required all talc products to be asbestos-free.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Separating cosmetic-grade talc (e.g. talcum powder) from industrial-grade talc (often used in friction products) has largely eliminated this issue for consumers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Cosmetics companies, including Johnson & Johnson, have known since the 1950s that talc products could be contaminated with asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In July 2024, the World Health Organization (WHO) heightened its health warning about talc exposure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2000, tests in a certified asbestos-testing laboratory found the tremolite form of amphibole asbestos used to be found in three out of eight popular brands of children's crayons that were made partly from talc: Crayola, Prang, and RoseArt.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In Crayola crayons, the tests found asbestos levels around 0.05% in *Carnation Pink* and 2.86% in *Orchid*; in Prang crayons, the range was from 0.3% in *Periwinkle* to 0.54% in *Yellow*; in Rose Art crayons, it was from 0.03% in *Brown* to 1.20% in *Orange*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Overall, 32 different types of crayons from these brands used to contain more than trace amounts of asbestos, and eight others contained trace amounts.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The Art and Creative Materials Institute, a trade association which tested the safety of crayons on behalf of the makers, initially insisted the test results must have been incorrect, although they later said they do not test for asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In May 2000, Crayola said tests by Richard Lee, a materials analyst whose testimony on behalf of the asbestos industry has been accepted in lawsuits over 250 times, found its crayons tested negative for asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Despite that, in June 2000 Binney & Smith, the maker of Crayola, and the other makers agreed to stop using talc in their products, and changed their product formulations in the United States.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The mining company R T Vanderbilt Co of Gouverneur, New York, which supplied the talc to the crayon makers, states that "to the best of our knowledge and belief" there had never been any asbestos-related disease among the company's workers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] However media reports claim that the United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA) had found asbestos in four talc samples tested in 2000.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] On 12 July 2018, a Missouri jury ordered Johnson & Johnson to pay a record $4.69 billion to 22 women who alleged the company's talc-based products, including its baby powder, contain asbestos and caused them to develop ovarian cancer.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2017, 1.3 million tonnes of asbestos were mined worldwide.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Russia was the largest producer with 53% of the world total, followed by Kazakhstan (16%), China (15%), and Brazil (11.5%).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asia consumes some 70% of the asbestos produced in the world with China, India and Indonesia being the largest consumers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2009, about 9% of the world's asbestos production was in Canada.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In late 2011, Canada's remaining two asbestos mines, both located in Quebec, halted operations.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In September 2012, the Quebec government halted asbestos mining.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The most common diseases associated with chronic asbestos exposure are asbestosis (scarring of the lungs due to asbestos inhalation) and mesothelioma (cancer associated with asbestos).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Mesothelioma is an aggressive form of cancer and often leads to a life expectancy of less than 12 months after diagnosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] All types of asbestos fibers are known to represent serious health hazards in humans and animals.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Exposure to asbestos in the form of fibers is always considered dangerous.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Working with, or exposure to, material that is friable, or materials or works that could cause the release of loose asbestos fibers, is considered high risk.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In general, people who become ill from inhaling asbestos have been regularly exposed in a job where they worked directly with the material.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has standards to protect workers from the hazards of exposure to asbestos in the workplace.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The permissible exposure limit for asbestos is 0.1 fiber per cubic centimeter of air as an eight-hour time-weighted average, with an excursion limit of 1.0 asbestos fibers per cubic centimeter over 30 minutes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Worldwide, 66 countries and territories (including all those in the European Union) have banned the use of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Exemptions for minor uses are permitted in some countries listed; however, all countries listed must have banned the use of all types of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The use of crocidolite (blue asbestos) was banned in 1967, while the use of amosite (brown asbestos) continued in the construction industry until the mid-1980s.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It was finally banned from building products in 1989, though it remained in gaskets and brake linings until 31 December 2003, and cannot be imported, used, or recycled.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos continues to be a problem in Australia.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Two out of three homes in Australia built between World War II and the early 1980s still contain asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Handlers of asbestos materials must have a B-Class license for bonded asbestos and an A-Class license for friable asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The town of Wittenoom, in Western Australia, was built around a (blue) asbestos mine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The entire town continues to be contaminated and has been disincorporated, allowing local authorities to remove references to Wittenoom from maps and road signs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In January 2024, asbestos was found in garden mulch supplied to dozens of sites including parks, playgrounds and schools across Sydney, triggering the Sydney asbestos mulch crisis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] As of 31 December 2018, it is illegal to import, manufacture, sell, trade, or use products made from asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] There are exemptions for its use in the chloralkali industry, the military, nuclear facilities, and for magnesium extraction from asbestos mining residues.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] On 23 July 2000, the Supreme Council of Environmental Protection of Iran banned any use of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In a note, the Council states that, after 44 years, if there is no replacement that is technically, economically, or financially suitable, the law is appealable and will be subject to review.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] On 22 November 2011, Iran's Environmental Protection Organization banned the use of asbestos completely.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It also banned all imports and exports of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] On 9 October 2011, the Supreme Council of Environmental Protection of Iran confirmed the new law and publicly announced it, updating and replacing the previous law.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Revelations that hundreds of workers had died in Japan over the previous few decades from diseases related to asbestos sparked a scandal in mid-2005.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 1984, the import of raw amphibole (blue and brown) asbestos into New Zealand was banned.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2002, the import of chrysotile (white) asbestos was also banned.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2015, the government announced that the importation of asbestos would be completely banned with very limited exceptions (expected to be applied to replacement parts for older machines) that would be reviewed on a case-by-case basis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] North-west of Nelson, in the Upper Takaka Valley, is New Zealand's only commercially harvested asbestos mine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] A low-grade Chrysotile was mined here from 1908 to 1917, but only 100 tons were washed and taken out by packhorse.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] A new power scheme enabled work to renew, and between 1940 and 1949, the Hume Company mined 40 tons a month.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] This continued to 1964, when, due to the short length of its fibre, the limited commercial viability forced mining to cease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In May 1997, the manufacture and use of crocidolite and amosite, commonly known as blue and brown asbestos, were fully banned in South Korea.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In January 2009, a full-fledged ban on all types of asbestos occurred when the government banned the manufacture, import, sale, storage, transport, or use of asbestos or any substance containing more than 0.1% of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2011, South Korea became the world's sixth country to enact an asbestos harm aid act, which entitles any Korean citizen to free lifetime medical care as well as monthly income from the government if they are diagnosed with an asbestos-related disease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In the United Kingdom, blue and brown asbestos materials were banned outright in 1985, while the import, sale, and secondhand reuse of white asbestos was outlawed in 1999.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Employers, e.g., construction companies, whose operatives may come into contact with asbestos, must also provide annual asbestos training to their workers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Since 2024, the United States has banned chrysotile asbestos, the only type of asbestos still used in the country.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] However, it would remain legal to import other types of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Companies would be required to notify the E.P.A. beforehand, and the agency would have the authority to deny those imports.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Before 2024, the United States remained one of the few developed countries to not completely ban asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Some American workers at chlorine plants frequently came in contact with the substance, and OSHA exempted these plants from random inspections through the Voluntary Protection Program.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 1989, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) issued the Asbestos Ban and Phase-Out Rule.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 1991, asbestos industry supporters challenged and overturned the ban in a landmark lawsuit: *Corrosion Proof Fittings v.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Although the case resulted in several small victories for asbestos regulation, the EPA ultimately did not put an end to asbestos use.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The ruling left many consumer products that can still legally contain trace amounts of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Six categories of asbestos-containing products are however banned: corrugated paper, rollboard, commercial paper, specialty paper, flooring felt and any new uses of asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The Clean Air Act also bans asbestos pipe insulation and asbestos block insulation on components such as boilers and hot water tanks, and spray-applied surfacing asbestos-containing materials.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The Consumer Product Safety Act bans asbestos in artificial fireplace embers and wall patching compounds.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The Food and Drug Administration bans asbestos-containing filters in pharmaceutical manufacturing, processing, and packing.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2014, the state of Washington banned asbestos in automotive brakes.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2022, 224 metric tons (220 long tons; 247 short tons) of chrysotile asbestos were imported into the United States from Brazil and Russia for use in diaphragms used to produce chlorine by the chloralkali process.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] As of 2020, imported goods containing asbestos included gaskets for some utility vehicles, rubber sheets used in gasket manufacturing, brake blocks for the oil industry, and vehicle friction materials such as aftermarket automotive brakes and linings.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2024, the EPA announced the Part 1 Chrysotile Asbestos rule banning chrysotile in six conditions of use by 2037.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In response to ongoing asbestos imports and use, the Alan Reinstein Ban Asbestos Now (ARBAN) Act (S.2811, H.R.5373) has been reintroduced in Congress.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The American Public Health Association, Asbestos Disease Awareness Organization (ADAO), Environmental Working Group, Collegium Ramazzini, the International Association of Fire Fighters, and others are early supporters.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] China has banned the use of highly carcinogenic Amphibole Asbestos since 2002.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] However, Chrysotile Asbestos is still in use.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] To safeguard the occupational health of workers, China has promulgated a standard that establishes occupational exposure limits for asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Since 1970, as a result of increased regulation of asbestos in Europe and in the United States, there was a massive transfer of asbestos-processing enterprises to Mexico.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Asbestos is used in many products – roofing, boilers, pipes, brakes, and wires- produced by over 2,000 Mexican companies, many of them subsidiaries or subcontractors of US companies, and sold throughout the Americas.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In 2000, 58% of Mexican asbestos-containing exports went to the United States, and 40% to Central American countries and Cuba.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] In Vietnam, chrysotile asbestos is not banned and is still widely used.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Amphibole asbestos is banned from trade and use.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] Vietnam is one of the top 10 asbestos users in the world, with an annual import volume of about 65,000–70,000 tons of chrysotile.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] About 90% of the imported asbestos is used to produce about 100 million m2 of cement roofing sheets (asbestos-cement).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] According to one study, among 300 families in Yen Bai, Thanh Hoa, 85% of households use asbestos roofing sheets, but only 5% know about the negative health effects.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The master plan (for construction materials development to 2020 with orientation to 2030 submitted by the Ministry of Construction to the Government in January 2014) still suggests continued use of chrysotile for a long time.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] The "Cincinnati method", or EPA/600/R-04/004, involves putting a sample of vermiculite into a large beaker of water, and then examining both the sunk and suspended particles using an optical microscope.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p01] It is also possible to detect asbestos in vermiculite by grinding the sample into a powder and then using an electron microscope.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Fiberglass insulation was invented in 1938 and is now the most commonly used type of insulation material.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] The safety of this material has also been called into question due to similarities in material structure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] However, the International Agency for Research on Cancer removed fiberglass from its list of possible human carcinogens in 2001.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] In 1978, a highly texturized fiberglass fabric, called Zetex, was invented by Bal Dixit.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] It is less dense than asbestos but offers the same bulk, thickness, hand, feel, and abrasion resistance.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] The fiberglass was texturized to eliminate some of the problems that arise with fiberglass, such as poor abrasion resistance and poor seam strength.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] In Europe, mineral wool and glass wool are the main insulators in houses.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Many companies that produced asbestos-cement products that were reinforced with asbestos fibers have developed products incorporating organic fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] One such product, known as "Eternit", and another, "Everite", now use "Nutec" which consists of organic fibers, portland cement and silica.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Cement-bonded wood fiber is another substitute.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Stone fibers are used in gaskets and friction materials.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Another potential fire-resistant material is polybenzimidazole or PBI.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Polybenzimidazole fiber is a synthetic fiber which has a high melting point of 760 °C (1,400 °F) and does not ignite.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Because of its exceptional thermal and chemical stability, it is often used by fire departments and space agencies.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] In most developed countries, asbestos is typically disposed of as hazardous waste in designated landfill sites.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] The demolition of buildings containing large amounts of asbestos-based materials poses particular problems for builders and property developers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Such buildings often have to be deconstructed piece by piece, or the asbestos has to be painstakingly removed before the structure can be razed by mechanical or explosive means.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] One such example is the Red Road Flats in Glasgow, Scotland, which used huge amounts of asbestos cement board for wall panelling.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] British health and safety regulations stipulate that asbestos material has to be removed in specially adapted vehicles and taken to a landfill site with an appropriate permit to accept asbestos, via an approved route, at certain times of the day.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] In the United States, the EPA governs the removal and disposal of asbestos strictly.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Companies that remove asbestos must comply with EPA licensing.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] These companies are called EPA-licensed asbestos contractors.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Anytime one of these asbestos contractors performs work, a test consultant has to conduct strict testing to ensure the asbestos is completely removed.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Asbestos can be destroyed by ultra-high-temperature incineration and plasma melting process.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] A process of thermal decomposition at 1,000–1,250 °C (1,800–2,300 °F) produces a mixture of non-hazardous silicon-based wastes, and at temperatures above 1,250 °C (2,300 °F) it produces silicate glass.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] Microwave thermal treatment can be used in an industrial manufacturing process to transform asbestos and asbestos-containing waste into porcelain stoneware tiles, porous single-fired wall tiles, and ceramic bricks.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestos-fibers-p02] The combination of oxalic acid with ultrasound fully degrades chrysotile asbestos fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestosis is caused by breathing in asbestos fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] It requires a relatively large exposure over a long period of time, which typically only occurs in those who directly work with asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] All types of asbestos fibers are associated with an increased risk.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] It is generally recommended that currently existing and undamaged asbestos be left undisturbed.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Diagnosis is based upon a history of exposure together with medical imaging.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestosis is a type of interstitial pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Recommendations may include influenza vaccination, pneumococcal vaccination, oxygen therapy, and stopping smoking.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestosis affected about 157,000 people and resulted in 3,600 deaths in 2015.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestos use has been banned in a number of countries in an effort to prevent disease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Statistics from the UK's Health and Safety Executive showed that in 2019, there were 490 asbestosis deaths.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The signs and symptoms of asbestosis typically manifest after a significant amount of time has passed following asbestos exposure, often several decades under current conditions in the US.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The primary symptom of asbestosis is generally the slow onset of shortness of breath, especially with physical activity.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Clinically advanced cases of asbestosis may lead to respiratory failure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] When a stethoscope is used to listen to the lungs of a person with asbestosis, they may hear inspiratory "crackles".
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The characteristic pulmonary function finding in asbestosis is a restrictive ventilatory defect.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This manifests as a reduction in lung volumes, particularly the vital capacity (VC) and total lung capacity (TLC).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The TLC may be reduced through alveolar wall thickening; however, this is not always the case.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Large airway function, as reflected by FEV1/FVC, is generally well preserved.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] In severe cases, the drastic reduction in lung function due to the stiffening of the lungs and reduced TLC may induce right-sided heart failure (cor pulmonale).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] In addition to a restrictive defect, asbestosis may produce reduction in diffusion capacity and a low amount of oxygen in the blood of the arteries.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The cause of asbestosis is the inhalation of microscopic asbestos mineral fibers suspended in the air.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Merewether found that greater exposure resulted in greater risk.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Those who worked in the production, milling, manufacturing, installation, or removal of asbestos products before the late 1970s are at an increased risk of exposure to asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This includes people who worked in these jobs in the United States and Canada.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Construction workers who inhale asbestos from contaminated building materials such as paint, spackling, roof shingles, masonry compounds, and drywall may get asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The amount and length of an individual's exposure to asbestos are the primary factors that determine the level of risk.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The longer one is exposed to the substance, the higher their risk of developing lung damage.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Families of exposed workers can be affected because asbestos fibers from clothing and hair can end up in the home.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] People who live near mines can also be exposed to airborne asbestos fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestosis is the scarring of lung tissue (beginning around terminal bronchioles and alveolar ducts and extending into the alveolar walls) resulting from the inhalation of asbestos fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] There are two types of fibers: amphibole (thin and straight) and serpentine (curly).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] All forms of asbestos fibers are responsible for human disease as they are able to penetrate deeply into the lungs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This inflammatory reaction can be described as chronic rather than acute, with a slow ongoing progression of the immune system attempting to eliminate the foreign fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Macrophages phagocytose (ingest) the fibers and stimulate fibroblasts to deposit connective tissue.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Due to the asbestos fibers' natural resistance to digestion, some macrophages release inflammatory chemical signals, and other macrophages are killed, releasing reactive oxygen species and activating transcription factors, like NF-κB, which amplify the expression of pro-inflammatory cytokines.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] These inflammatory chemical signals attract further lung macrophages and fibrolastic cells that synthesize fibrous scar tissue, which eventually becomes diffuse and can progress in heavily exposed individuals.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This tissue can be seen microscopically soon after exposure in animal models.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Some asbestos fibers become layered by an iron-containing proteinaceous material (ferruginous body) in cases of heavy exposure where about 10% of the fibers become coated.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Most inhaled asbestos fibers remain uncoated.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] About 20% of the inhaled fibers are transported by cytoskeletal components of the alveolar epithelium to the interstitial compartment of the lung where they interact with macrophages and mesenchymal cells.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The cytokines, transforming growth factor beta and tumor necrosis factor alpha, appear to play major roles in the development of scarring inasmuch as the process can be blocked in animal models by preventing the expression of the growth factors.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The result is fibrosis in the interstitial space, thus asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This fibrotic scarring causes alveolar walls to thicken, which reduces elasticity and gas diffusion, reducing oxygen transfer to the blood as well as the removal of carbon dioxide.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] This can result in shortness of breath, a common symptom exhibited by individuals with asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Those with asbestosis may be more vulnerable to tumor growth (mesothelioma), because asbestos decreases the cytotoxicity of natural killer cells and impairs the functioning of T helper cells, which detect abnormal cell growth.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The abnormal chest x-ray and its interpretation remain the most important factors in establishing the presence of pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The findings usually appear as small, irregular parenchymal opacities, primarily in the lung bases.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Using the ILO Classification system, "s", "t", and/or "u" opacities predominate.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] CT or high-resolution CT (HRCT) are more sensitive than plain radiography at detecting pulmonary fibrosis (as well as any underlying pleural changes).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] More than 50% of people affected with asbestosis develop plaques in the parietal pleura, the space between the chest wall and lungs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Once apparent, the radiographic findings in asbestosis may slowly progress or remain static, even in the absence of further asbestos exposure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Rapid progression suggests an alternative diagnosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestosis resembles many other diffuse interstitial lung diseases, including other pneumoconiosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The differential diagnosis includes idiopathic pulmonary fibrosis (IPF), hypersensitivity pneumonitis, sarcoidosis, and others.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The presence of pleural plaques may provide supportive evidence of causation by asbestos.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Although lung biopsy is usually not necessary, the presence of asbestos bodies in association with pulmonary fibrosis establishes the diagnosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Conversely, interstitial pulmonary fibrosis in the absence of asbestos bodies is most likely not asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Asbestos bodies in the absence of fibrosis indicate exposure, not disease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] There is no cure available for asbestosis.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Oxygen therapy at home is often necessary to relieve the shortness of breath and correct underlying low blood oxygen levels.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Supportive treatment of symptoms includes respiratory physiotherapy to remove secretions from the lungs by postural drainage, chest percussion, and vibration.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Nebulized medications may be prescribed in order to loosen secretions or treat underlying chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Immunization against pneumococcal pneumonia and annual influenza vaccination is administered due to increased sensitivity to the diseases.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Those with asbestosis are at increased risk for certain cancers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] If the person smokes, quitting the habit reduces further damage.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Periodic pulmonary function tests, chest x-rays, and clinical evaluations, including cancer screening/evaluations, are given to detect additional hazards.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Montague Murray, M.D., F.R.C.P., testified before a British committee concerning a patient who died in April 1900.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Murray indicated that fibrosis of the lungs caused by asbestos dust was a plausible cause of the patient's death.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The death of English textile worker Nellie Kershaw in 1924 from pulmonary asbestosis was the first case to be described in medical literature, and the first published account of disease definitely attributed to occupational asbestos exposure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] However, her former employers (Turner Brothers Asbestos) denied that asbestosis even existed because the medical condition was not officially recognised at the time.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] As a result, they accepted no liability for her injuries and paid no compensation, either to Kershaw during her final illness or to her family after her death.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Even so, the findings of the inquest into her death were highly influential insofar as they led to a parliamentary enquiry by the British Parliament.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The enquiry formally acknowledged the existence of asbestosis, recognised that it was hazardous to health and concluded that it was irrefutably linked to the prolonged inhalation of asbestos dust.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Having established the existence of asbestosis on a medical and judicial basis, the report resulted in the first Asbestos Industry Regulations being published in 1931, which came into effect on 1 March 1932.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The first lawsuits against asbestos manufacturers occurred in 1929.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Since then, many lawsuits have been filed against asbestos manufacturers and employers, for neglecting to implement safety measures after the link between asbestos, asbestosis and mesothelioma became known (some reports seem to place this as early as 1898 in modern times).
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The liability resulting from the sheer number of lawsuits and people affected has reached billions of U.S. dollars.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] The amounts and method of allocating compensation have been the source of many court cases, and government attempts at resolution of existing and future cases.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] To date, about 100 companies have declared bankruptcy at least partially due to asbestos-related liability.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] In accordance with Chapter 11 and § 524(g) of the U.S. federal bankruptcy code, a company may transfer its liabilities and certain assets to an asbestos personal injury trust, which is then responsible for compensating present and future claimants.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] Since 1988, 60 trusts have been established to pay claims with about $37 billion in total assets.
[src:babcock-wilcox/asbestosis] From 1988 through 2010, analysis from the United States Government Accountability Office indicates that trusts have paid about 3.3 million claims valued at about $17.5 billion.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The **B&W mPower** was a proposed small modular reactor designed by Babcock & Wilcox, and to be built by Generation mPower LLC, a joint venture of Babcock & Wilcox and Bechtel.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] It was a Generation III+ integral pressurized water reactor (light water reactor) concept.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In March 2017, Bechtel withdrew from the joint venture and the project was terminated.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The reactor was unveiled by Babcock & Wilcox in June 2009.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In July 2010, Babcock & Wilcox announced a formal alliance with Bechtel called Generation mPower LLC.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] At the same time, Babcock & Wilcox announced that it would build a test facility for the mPower reactor design at the Center for Advanced Engineering and Research in Bedford County, Virginia.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In April 2011, Babcock & Wilcox received a $5 million grant from the Virginia Tobacco Indemnification and Community Revitalisation Commission for this test facility.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In June 2011 Generation mPower signed a letter of intent with the Tennessee Valley Authority for constructing up to six reactors at Clinch River Breeder Reactor site in Tennessee.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Generation mPower planned to apply to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission for design certification by 2013.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Babcock & Wilcox announced on February 20, 2013, that they had contracted with the Tennessee Valley Authority to apply for permits to build an mPower small modular reactor at TVA's Clinch River site in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In November 2012, mPower won a US Department of Energy funding competition for new Small modular reactor (SMR) designs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The competition was intended to accelerate development of SMRs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The award was funded at $79 million in 2013, from a total of $150 million over five years, with a possibility of total government grants reaching $226 million or more.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In 2013 Babcock & Wilcox had intended to sell a majority stake in the mPower joint venture, but in February 2014 announced it was unable to find a buyer.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In February 2014, Jim Ferland, B&W's CEO, announced that spending on the mPower reactor development will be decreased by 75%.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The official explanation was that the company had failed in its effort to find additional major investors to participate in the project.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In April 2014, Babcock & Wilcox announced it was scaling back investment in the programme, projecting investment of up to $15 million annually.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In March 2017 Bechtel withdrew from the joint venture, citing the inability to find a utility company that would provide a site for a first reactor and an investor.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The development project was terminated, with Babcock & Wilcox paying Bechtel a $30 million settlement.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] B&W mPower was a Generation III+ integral pressurized water reactor (light water reactor) with a modular design.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The reactor and steam generator would be located in a single integrated reactor vessel located in an underground containment facility that would store all of the spent fuel.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The modular unit had a diameter of 4.5 metres (15 ft) and it was 23 metres (75 ft) high.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The reactor core was 2 by 2 metres (6 ft 7 in by 6 ft 7 in).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The steam generator was similar to Once Through Steam Generators (OTSG) used in existing B&W plants (i.e.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The unit had an air-cooled condenser giving 31% thermal efficiency, and passive safety systems.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The reactor was planned to have a rated electrical output of 125–180 MWe.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] When originally announced, the reactor had planned capacity of 125 MWe.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Later the power was increased to 160 MWe and then to 180 MWe.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] In its pre-application design certification interaction with the Nuclear Regulatory Commission, the reactor's rated capacity was described as 500MWt of thermal power and 160 MWe of electrical power.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The reactor was designed for an expected lifetime of 60 years.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] B&W mPower uses standard fuel enriched to 5%, similar to the fuel loaded in the other PWRs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] It was designed for a 4-year refueling cycle.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The entire used core, once removed, can be placed in storage in the spent fuel pool next to the IRV in the containment, which was designed to hold an entire 60 years worth of used fuel, and was accessible by the containment gantry crane located above the IRV within the containment.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The mPower incorporates several features of the boiling water reactor (BWR).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Like a BWR, the mPower reactor's primary coolant/moderator was highly purified water (with no boric acid).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The Reactor Water Cleanup System ensures that primary system water remains pure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Similar to the ABWR, the mPower reactor had integral coolant recirculation pumps inside the Integral Reactor Vessel (IRV).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The mPower reactor control rods are inserted from the top of the core and inserted upon scram under gravity.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] All of the primary coolants were in the liquid phase during normal operation.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The integral once-through steam generator was an advanced derivative of the steam generators used in older B&W designs (Davis Besse).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Control rod drives do not penetrate the IRV, as in the light water reactors of today, but are instead wholly enclosed within the IRV.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Burnable neutron absorbers within the fuel and control rod inventory are used to suppress hot excess reactivity.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Cold shut-down was accomplished with control rod insertion (as in BWRs).
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The mPower was designed to produce superheated steam and would not require steam separators and dryers before admitting steam into the high-pressure turbine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] The mPower was designed to eliminate the potential loss of coolant accidents as the integral reactor vessel would not have a large cold or hot leg piping; it contains the entire primary coolant loop within the reactor pressure vessel with automatic primary loop depressurization.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] If secondary cooling was lost, creating an effective loss of standard heat removal, there are water supplies located above and within the containment that can cool the vessel with gravity-driven cooling.
[src:babcock-wilcox/b-w-mpower] Heat removal can be used if these systems are exhausted, such as by flooding the containment and establishing natural circulation, as no electrically driven pumps are required.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The company was founded in 1867 in Providence, Rhode Island, by partners Stephen Wilcox and George Babcock to manufacture and market Wilcox's patented water-tube boiler.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1867, Stephen Wilcox, Jr. and his partner George Herman Babcock, of Providence, Rhode Island, patented their so-called safety boiler ("Improvements in Steam Generators", U.S.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Its water was dispersed in many small tubes that resisted exploding when heated, a significant advance over conventional shell boilers, whose water was concentrated in a single container.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] When overheated, seams of the shell could burst, causing an explosion, often with fatal consequences.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The water tube boiler had the added advantages that it could generate steam under higher pressure and more efficiently than existing designs.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1878, Thomas Edison purchased B&W boiler No.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1891, Babcock & Wilcox Ltd was established as a separate United Kingdom company, to be responsible for all sales outside the US and Cuba.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1895, B&W supplied of steam furnaces of Kahrizak sugar factory, Tehran, Iran.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1898, Robert Jurenka and Alois Seidl signed an agreement with the British division, Babcock & Wilcox Ltd, to make the Berlin, Germany Babcock sales office into a subsidiary of the British company; a factory in Oberhausen in the Ruhr district made the boiler designed by the American engineers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1902, New York City's first subway line was powered by B&W boilers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] During 1907 and 1909, Theodore Roosevelt's Great White Fleet were powered by B&W Boilers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1915, The Babcock & Wilcox Company acquired the Dumbarton Weldless Tube Company Ltd., originally Kosmoid Tubes Ltd., with works in Dumbarton, Scotland (operational until 1997).
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1923, both Babcock & Wilcox Ltd and The Babcock & Wilcox Company bought into The Goldie & McCulloch Company Ltd of Cambridge, Ontario, to form Babcock-Wilcox & Goldie-McCulloch Ltd in Canada.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1929, B&W installed the world's first commercial size recovery boiler using the magnesium bisulfite process in Quebec, Canada.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Between 1941 and 1945, B&W designed and delivered 4,100 marine boilers for combat and merchant ships, including 95 percent of the US fleet in Tokyo Bay at Japanese surrender.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1942, the company developed the cyclone furnace.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Between 1943 and 1945, B&W provided components, materials and process development for Manhattan Project.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1948, Babcock and Wilcox was at the center of a labor dispute with the United Stone and Allied Products Workers of America.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The National Labor Relations Board held that during captive audience meetings, the union was entitled to equal time.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Between 1949 and 1952, B&W provided the 8 boilers for the SS *United States*, the fastest ocean liner ever constructed.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Between 1953 and 1955, B&W designed and fabricated components for USS *Nautilus* (SSN-571), world's first nuclear-powered submarine.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1961, B&W designed and supplied reactors for world's first commercial nuclear ship NS *Savannah*.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1962, B&W designed and furnished reactor systems for B&W's first commercial reactor, Indian Point, NY, using HEU 233.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1967, the name of Babcock-Wilcox & Goldie-McCulloch Ltd is changed to Babcock & Wilcox Canada Ltd.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1975, B&W designed and built components for liquid metal fast breeder reactors.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1975, the long-term business agreements with the British Babcock & Wilcox Ltd were ended.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Subsequently, the British company was renamed Babcock International Group plc.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1978, B&W designed and built the nuclear reactor that was involved in the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1983, A known, unreported design failure in a B&W valve was found to be an initial cause for the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 1999, B&W was awarded the contract to develop fuel cells and steam reforming for US Navy.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On February 22, 2000, B&W filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in part as a result of thousands of claims for personal injury due to prolonged exposure to asbestos and asbestos fibers.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] Claims included asbestosis, lung cancer, pleural and peritoneal mesothelioma.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] As a condition of emerging from bankruptcy, B&W created a trust fund to compensate victims for amounts far less than settlements paid in individual personal injury lawsuits.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] After B&W emerged from bankruptcy in 2006, B&W and BWX Technologies, both subsidiaries of the McDermott International, Inc., merged on 26 November 2007 to form The Babcock & Wilcox Companies, headed by President John Fees.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On June 10, 2009, B&W unveiled B&W Modular Nuclear Energy, LLC (B&W MNE).
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On the same day, B&W MNE announced its plans to design and develop the B&W mPower reactor, a modular, scalable nuclear reactor.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The B&W mPower reactor design is a 125 megawatt, passively safe Advanced Light Water Reactor (ALWR) (a Generation III reactor) with a below-ground containment structure.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The reactor is set to be manufactured in a factory, shipped by rail, then buried underground.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On May 12, 2010, B&W announced that it and its subsidiaries would be spun off from its parent company, McDermott International, Inc.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The headquarters moved from Lynchburg, Virginia to Charlotte. and the company became The Babcock & Wilcox Company.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On August 2, 2010, B&W began trading on the New York Stock Exchange as BWC.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On June 30, 2015, Babcock & Wilcox completed a spinoff from BWX Technologies, its former parent company.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] The two companies began trading separately on July 1 when Babcock & Wilcox Enterprises, Inc. was listed on the New York Stock Exchange under the ticker symbol: BW.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] In 2016, in the UK, the company was ordered to change its name following a petition filed by Babcock International.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On September 24, 2018, Babcock & Wilcox announced that it would move its corporate headquarters from Charlotte to Akron, Ohio, into space formerly occupied by the Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company prior to its move to a new building nearby.
[src:babcock-wilcox/babcock-wilcox] On December 30, 2019, Babcock & Wilcox relocated its corporate headquarters from Barberton, Ohio, to Akron, Ohio.
